The paper discusses the ethical implications of artificial general intelligence (AGI) and proposes a spectrum of principles for nurturing agents with different experiences and objectives. This suggests a focus on the development, design, training, and release of autonomous agents, which are relevant to the fields of artificial intelligence (AI) and robotics (RO). The paper also mentions the need to weave ethics into advancing ML research, which falls under the category of human-computer interaction (HC). Additionally, the paper discusses the implications of AGI on society, which could fall under the categories of cybersecurity (CY) and machine learning (LG).
